<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="space-y-6">
<div>
<h3>What makes Bordeaux different from other wine regions?</h3>
<p>Bordeaux's unique terroir combines maritime climate, diverse soils, and centuries of blending expertise. The region's Left Bank/Right Bank division creates distinct styles within one appellation, while the classification system provides quality guidance unmatched elsewhere.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Should beginners start with Left Bank or Right Bank Bordeaux?</h3>
<p>Right Bank wines offer better entry points due to their softer tannins and earlier drinking windows. Merlot-dominant blends provide more immediate fruit character, making them easier to appreciate without extensive wine knowledge or long cellaring.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How do I identify a quality Bordeaux at reasonable prices?</h3>
<p>Focus on Cru Bourgeois estates, lesser-known appellations like Fronsac or Côtes de Bordeaux, and good vintages from classified growths. Avoid trophy names and seek recommendations from knowledgeable retailers who specialize in Bordeaux.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>When should I drink my Bordeaux wines?</h3>
<p>Basic Bordeaux drinks within 3-5 years, commune-level wines peak at 7-12 years, and classified growths need 10-20+ years. Check vintage charts and producer recommendations, as drinking windows vary significantly by estate and weather conditions.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What's the proper way to store Bordeaux long-term?</h3>
<p>Maintain consistent temperature around 55°F, keep humidity at 70%, store bottles horizontally in darkness, and minimize vibration. Consider professional storage for valuable collections, as improper conditions can ruin expensive wines within months.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How can I tell if my aged Bordeaux is still good?</h3>
<p>Check cork condition, wine level, and color through the bottle. Healthy wines maintain deep color and show no leakage signs. When opened, good wines display complex aromatics without vinegar, wet cardboard, or medicinal odors.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Are Bordeaux futures worth buying?</h3>
<p>En primeur purchases work best for allocated wines from top estates in exceptional vintages. Calculate total costs including storage and delivery before committing. Most consumers benefit more from buying mature wines ready for immediate consumption.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What food works best with different Bordeaux styles?</h3>
<p>Left Bank wines match red meat, game, and aged cheeses due to their tannin structure. Right Bank styles complement duck, lamb, and mushroom dishes. White Bordeaux suits seafood, poultry, and cream-based preparations perfectly.</p>
</div>
